Pantagruel reflects on the particular gifts which by the divine goodness have been heaped on him and since his departure it has banished all other thoughts from his mind. He sends Malicorne to give him a true account of his health at the beginning of his voyage. Panurge tells that if they touch at the great kingdom of Gebarim, they would be honorably received and treated by the sovereign of that country, King Ohabe. Friar John relates how Basche, a brave, honest, noble-spirited gentleman, was every day cited, warned, and prosecuted at the suit and for the sport and fancy of the fat prior of St. Louant. Pantagruel shoots the physeter with darts and it dies. He demands a parley with the queen, who offers to hold of him and his the whole island and country to obey him in all his commands.

Vivie, a 22 year old educated middle-class Englishwoman, meets Praed, an anarchist born artist who hates authority. He arranges for her to come down from London to meet her. Vivie explains that she came down to read law not for a holiday as her mother imagines. Praed says he hopes they can be friends. Vivie says she hopes he is disposed to be. Mrs. Warren and Sir George Crofts arrive at the gate. Mrs. Warren sits in Praed's chair and fanning herself. Crofts says he hopes it will pass off presently. Frank Gardner appears on the common and says he's glad Vivie knows him.

Rev. Gardner says silence. Frank says he once offered a woman 50 pounds for the letters he wrote to her when. Rev. Gardner says he put himself into her power and she never made use of her power or caused him a moment's uneasiness.
Mrs. Warren breaks down and says she sent it back to be placed to your credit and asked them to send you the lodgment receipt. In future she'll support herself.

Major Carteret, a wealthy white man, has always maintained that the white and black races could never attain social and political harmony by commingling their blood. He has invested his wife's inheritance in a local cotton mill, which is paying 10% interest. General Belmont and Captain McBane visit Carteret to congratulate him on the birth of his child. Miller, a medical professor, notices a singular thing about the man as he passes the rear coach. Carteret leads the way to the nursery where the operation is to take place. Dr. Burns assures Miller that there is no danger in telling the truth.

Ellis hears a story about Tom Delamere which he imagines would spike that gentleman's guns for all time. The reporter announces that the murderer is a negro, the victim a white woman. Carteret argues that if the negro is innocent, then Delamere must produce the real criminal.

Dr. Miller receives a call to attend a case at the house of a well-to-do colored farmer. Josh and his men make their appearance in the negro quarter armed with guns and axes. A shot splinters the window casing close to Josh's head. Jerry scans the crowd looking for white friends. Carteret moves away after his futile effort to stem the torrent.
Sir Walter Elliot, of Kellynch Hall, never takes up a book but the Baronetage. He finds consolation in contemplating the limited remnant of the earliest patents.
Lady Elliot had been an excellent woman, sensible and amiable. Anne Elliot, now 19, likes the man for himself and more for being her father's heir. However, he has disappointed her.

Anne throws herself into an engagement with a young man who has nothing to recommend him and no hopes of attaining affluence. Captain Wentworth, her brother, finds a home at Monkford and they are quickly and deeply in love. Anne hopes that her past is known only to three among her connexions.

Anne would have been more thankful to ascertain that her father wasn't in love with Mrs Clay. The next morning, she finds that Mrs Clay has just pretended to mean to leave them. In the course of the same morning, Anne and her father chance to be alone together. He begins to compliment her on her improved looks thinking her less thin in person.
Anne meets the Admiral at a printshop. He takes her for a walk and says that Miss Louisa Musgrove instead of being to marry Frederick is to marry James Benwick.
Gabriel Oak leases a sheep farm and becomes infatuated with Bathsheba, a beautiful young woman. He asks her aunt for her hand in marriage, but she turns him down because she doesn't love him.

Bathsheba rejects Boldwood's proposal, explaining that she doesn't feel the same level of passion for him as he does for her. Boldwood realizes he's been blaming Bathsheba for Troy's actions, and apologizes to her.

Athens, TIMON'S house. Enter POET, PAINTER, JEWELLER, MERCHANT, and MERCER. POET says he knows the merchant. PAINTER shows a jewel for the Lord Timon. MERCHANT says it's a worthy lord. POET says their poetry is as a gum which oozes from whence it's nourished. PAINTER says how all conditions, minds, and creatures, as well of glib and slippy creatures as grave and austere, tender their services to Lord Timon. TIMON says he will pay the debt and free him. OLD ATHENIAN says Lord Timon, hear me speak. TIMON says freely. OLD ATHENIAN says you have a servant named Lucilius. TIMON says he has so. LUCILIUS says humbly he thanks your lordship. Exeunt LUCILIUS and O

Timon, a nobleman, has one word to say to his friends: look, he must entreat you honor him so much as to advance this jewel. First Lord Lucius and his men are also in attendance. Lucius tells Flavius that he has noted him always wise and prompt. Lucius then tells Flaminius that he cannot want for money. The second stranger says that not long ago one of his men was with the Lord Lucullus to borrow so many talents.
Enter Titus and Hortensius. Titus says that the like to him, and Lucius' servant says that his is money.
Flaminius says that he needs not tell him that he knows you are diligent.

Timon looks back upon thee, wall that girds in wolves, dive in the earth and fence not Athens! Matrons, turn incontinent. Obedience, fail in children! Slaves and fools, pluck the grave wrinkled Senate from the bench and minister in their steads. To general filths convert, o' th' instant, green virginity.

ALCIBIADES enters with drum and fife in warlike manner. Timon says that he is Misanthropos and hates mankind. ALCIBIADES says that he has little gold of late and that he is his friend and pity him. He says that he seeks to vex him.
Proteus wishes Valentine well and commends him to his prayers if ever danger environ him. Valentine says he will be his headsman.
Speed says that his master is a shepherd and that he gave Valentine's letter to Julia, a lac'd mutton.
Enter Proteus and Julia in boy's clothes. Proteus says that Sebastian is thy name and that he hopes that you will.
Julia says that she hopes her master's suit will be cold since she respects her mistress' love so much.

Phileas Fogg and Aouda descend into the cabin at midnight, having been preceded by Fix, who lies down on one of the cots. The next morning, they reach the coast and John Bunsby asserts that they will reach Shanghai in time.

John never intended for anyone to know about his secret, but since his mouth was forced open early on, he's decided to make the most of it. He values his character enough to be careful not to let it lapse. He's careful not to bring up his obsession with May, as he feels it's best to keep the topic light and familiar. May begins to observe John's life in the light of what she knows about him.

May and John have been friends for a long time. May knows John's secret and helps him pass as a normal man. John is afraid of something but doesn't know what. May eventually confesses to John that she fears she has a disorder in her blood. John worries that she might die before she has the chance to see what she's been waiting to see. As May's condition grows more serious, John becomes increasingly aware of his own age. He wonders if he will be associated with any sort of awful crash or ignominy as he ages. One afternoon, John visits May and notices she appears much older than before. He feels strangely abandoned by her. He doesn't directly ask May what she knows, but instead asks her what she thinks the worst thing that could happen to him could be. May asks why he assumes she hasn't lost her power to conceive such things.

Gargantua wins the battle against Picrochole's army and decides to forgive the Canarians and let them go free. He appoints Ponocrates as the overseer of the kingdom and orders that Marquet and the other people responsible for the war be handed over to him.

Pantagruel grows in size and strength while still in his mother's womb. He becomes so strong that he breaks free of his chains and eats his cradle. His father sends him to school to learn and grow in virtue.

Panurge explains how he escaped from the Turks. He explains that he often paid men to have sex with old women, and that he sued the women of the city for wearing high neckcloths. He is a very dishonest man, but he is also the most virtuous man in the world.

Trouillogan says that Panurge should do both marry and not marry. Pantagruel sees Panurge acting foolishly and tells him to seek advice from a fool, as it has saved many people in the past. Trouillogan cites several examples of how those considered fools are actually wise.
Pantagruel believes Bridlegoose should be pardoned because of his old age and his history of upright judgments.
The Chitterlings attack, but the cooks defeat them. Queen Niphleseth offers to hold the island and country in fealty to Pantagruel, who accepts.

Many months have passed since Phil last saw Mr. George. Mr. Smallweed brings his granddaughter Judy to see him. Grandfather Smallweed refers to Phil with a glance of terror and a half-subdued "O Lord!" Nor in his apprehension, on the surface of things, without some reason. Trooper takes a step or two away to lay it aside.
Sir Leicester Dedlock has got the better of the family gout and is once more upon his legs. The fashionable intelligence proclaims that Lady Dedlock is expected to return to town for a few weeks.

When Mr. Woodcourt arrives in London, he goes immediately to Mr. Vholes in Symond's Inn. For he never once from the moment when I entreated him to be a friend to Richard, neglected or forgot his promise. Mr. Vholes informs him that he has already mentioned the number and that if Richard continues to play for this considerable stake, he must have funds.

North of Garthdale, in the bottom of the dale, is the village of Garth. Under the mystery and terror of its solitude, it crouches from its topmost roof to the bowed back of its stone bridge. The three sisters, Mary, Alice, and Gwenda, have been there 5 months to-day. Alice thinks her father buried them there because he thinks he's punishing her.

As the door closes on them, Alice says she's in trouble and that they've been trying to get it out of her by bullying. Gwenda says she'll take her away with her tomorrow. Alice insists she killed her father. Ally tightens her hold on Ally through her fear.
Three years pass and six months. Mary invites Gwenda into her room to watch her to see if she would flinch before the signs of Steven's occupation.
Tess Durbeyfield visits Alec, Alec's father, to tell him that they are of the same family. Alec gathers specimens of the fruit for Tess. Tess decides to go to work.

Angel Clare, the youngest son of the parson, never entered the Church and his father was shocked. Angel spends years and years in desultory studies and meditations. Tess, a maid in the dairyman's household, becomes attracted to Angel. Angel feels oppressed by the outward heats and is burdened inwardly by waxing fervour of passion for the soft and silent Tess. Clare agrees to marry Crick, a wealthy man.

Alec, a wealthy man, marries Tess, a servant girl. One night, Clare is stabbed in his bed by an unknown assailant. Tess is distraught and believes Clare's brother Cuthbert is responsible. Clare leads Tess onward, growing weary for they had wandered a dozen or fifteen miles.

Antony receives news that his wife, Fulvia, has died. He decides to break off his relationship with Cleopatra and return to Rome to fight against Pompey. Cleopatra pretends to be upset by the news, but asks him to stay.
In Rome, Caesar reads a letter and is displeased with Antony's behavior. He decides to assemble his army to fight against Pompey.
In Syria, Ventidius and his men arrive with the dead body of Pacorus.
Ventidius says he has avenged Marcus Crassus' death and will inform Antony of their victory. Caesar, Antony, Lepidus, and Octavia meet and discuss their agreement.

Who wrought my studious numbers once in happier days now perforce in tears and sadness. Lo, the Muses guide my pen and voice my woe. Down their cheeks unfeigned the tear drops flow to my sad complainings. These alone in danger's hour have dared attend on the footsteps of the exile to his lonely journey's end. Old? Ah yes, swift, ere I knew it, by these sorrows on me pressed age hath come. Death passes by the wretched, but She appeared to be of our age and time. First, will you suffer me to test your mind so that I may learn how to set about your cure? She says: This world of ours, do you think it is governed haphazardly or is there any rational guidance? I say no, in no way may I deem that such fixed motions can be determined by random hazard. If you wish to impose a law of staying and departing on her whom you have chosen for your mistress, you are acting wrongfully.

Huck and Jim, who also ran away from Miss Watson, hide on an island in the Mississippi river. Huck dresses up as a girl named Sarah Williams and talks to a woman in town who tells him to go talk to her uncle Abner Moore. Huck successfully fools the men who approach the raft, claiming his father has smallpox.
The Grangerford family has a longstanding feud with the Shepherdsons. One day, Sophia runs away to marry Harney Shepherdson.

Tom Sawyer returns to town and tells Sally and Silas he knows where Jim is. The next morning, Tom and Huck plan to free Jim from his chains by sawing through the bed leg he's chained to. They write a letter warning the people that there is a gang of cutthroats from the Indian Territory who are going to steal the runaway slave that night.

Everyone is shocked that Jim managed to steal so many things from the house and fool everyone, including the dogs. The men chain Jim up again and plan to hang him as an example to other slaves, but decide against it as they don't want to pay for him. Tom tells Mrs. Hotchkiss how he and Huck managed to free Jim, angering her. He says Jim is already a free man as his former owner Miss Watson had set him free in her will. Everyone treats Jim well and gives him food and a good time.

Boethius lies in bed, suffering from lethargy. Philosophy appears and explains that he has banished himself from his country. She commends Boethius for his service to the commonweal, but he wonders why the innocent suffer while the wicked prosper.
Orpheus plays his music to persuade the monarch of the shades to give him back his bride, but he looks at Eurydice as they pass the gates of Hell, and loses her.

The village lies under two feet of snow, with drifts at the windy corners. Ethan Frome walks past the bank and Michael Eady's new brick store, past the church with its narrow peristyle. As he walks toward it, the upper windows draw a black arcade along the side wall of the building. Ethan thinks of his father's death and the misfortunes that followed it.

Ethan moves away toward the kitchen and his glance crosses Mattie's. As she mounts the stairs ahead of Zeena, Ethan undresses hurriedly and blows out the light so he won't see her when he takes his place at her side. Ethan feels confused that there are many things he ought to think about, but through his tingling veins and tired brain, he knows that Zeena had spoken the truth in saying that she had sat up because she felt "too mean" to sleep. Ethan's family and his house are the only ones Zeena goes to, drawn there by the fact that Mrs. Hale, in her youth, had done more "doctoring" than any other woman in Starkfield.

Ethan laughs and says, "Well, she'll have to say it to the cat any way!" He kneels down at Mattie's side to scrape up the pickles. Ethan says, "Here, give them to her." They finish supper and while Mattie clears the table Ethan goes to look at the cows. The next morning, Ethan tells Jotham to harness the greys. As soon as dinner is over Ethan sets out again for the wood-lot. He hopes Zeena hasn't broken anything she set store by. Ethan finds Mattie alone and she says, "Zeena's come." Ethan is shocked and says, "But the sorrel's not in the barn." Zeena says, "I thought you were to get 50 dollars from Andrew Hale for that lumber."

That evening, Theodore gains admittance into the private withdrawing room where the Veiled Lady is accustomed to retire. There he waits, listening to the stifled hum of the great audience. Suddenly, a veiled figure stands in the center of the room.

Fauntleroy spends years in guilt and flees his wife's death. His only brother adopted the forsaken child. She grows up in affluence with native graces around her. In her triumphant progress towards womanhood, she lacks a mother's care.

Jurgis asks the woman where his people went. She says she knows nothing. His brain is so confused that he can't grasp the situation. Grandmother Majauszkiene comes to the door and cries out when she sees Jurgis. She says the family moved and couldn't pay the rent and were turned out into the snow. Jurgis runs to Madame Haupt, a Dutchwoman who is frying pork and onions. Ona is lying on a pallet of rags and blankets. Jurgis calls to her but she doesn't stir. She is dead.

Jurgis reads a denunciation of the packers by Scully who declares that if they don't treat their people better the city authorities will tear down their plants. Now Scully asks Jurgis why he didn't stick by his job. Jurgis debates on the way and decides to get 3 dollars a day. He becomes one of the new American heroes. Back to "Packers' Avenue," Jurgis sees one of his companions narrating how the four were attacked and nearly torn to pieces.

Jurgis becomes an outcast and a tramp after being arrested for assault. He is lucky to get a job at a restaurant where he can eat and sleep. One day, Jurgis meets Fisher, a Chicago millionaire who has given up his life to settlement work. The Socialist vote is over four hundred thousand, an increase of three hundred and fifty percent in four years. Chicago now leads the country.
Camillo and Vittoria discuss their marriage. Flamineo suggests that Camillo lock up his wife to prevent her from being unfaithful. Camillo agrees to Flamineo's plan.
Fran says that Vittoria is Brachiano's whore. The two threaten to fight each other.
Monticelso says that Vittoria is a whore and that she will be confined to a house of convertites. Brachiano enters and says he wishes her well.
The Pope has signed Brachiano's pardon at the request of the Duke of Florence. Lodo says that Vittoria is a whore. Flamineo strikes Lodo and laughs.
Isabella's ghost appears before him, but he realizes it is just his imagination.
Zanche says that he will not live after Vittoria dies, and that he will shoot himself with two pistols. He and Vittoria shoot themselves, and then run to him and tread on him.

Serebrakoff, Helena, and Sonia are in the dining room of Serebrakoff's house. Serebrakoff says he's spent his life working for success and fame, but now he's in exile with nothing to do but fear death. Helena tells him to have patience as she'll be old herself in a few years.

Christy Mahon enters the pub and explains that he killed his father a week ago. He says he hit his father on the head with a shovel and buried him in a field. Michael offers him a job as a pot boy, and Pegeen convinces him to stay in the shop for the night since he's exhausted from walking.
Widow Quin arrives to take Christy in, saying that the priest and Shawn think it's inappropriate for him to be staying with an orphaned girl.

Lady Sneerwell and Miss Verjuice discuss their gossip campaign's success. Lady Sneerwell explains that Sir Peter has two sons, one of whom is respectable while the other is wild and extravagant. She is secretly interested in the wild son, Charles.
Mrs. Candour arrives and asks about the rumors of Maria and Charles' breakup. Maria becomes upset and leaves the room.

Henry decides to join the army but his father takes his decision quietly. Henry decides to stay in London to support his parents. His work as a private secretary is exhausting as he must face a hostile society and pretend to be calm and collected.

Henry works hard to understand the tangled demonstration that begins in June 1862. As the Union army is driven from Washington and the Army of the Potomac is dispersed, Russell suggests that intervention might be feasible.

On a ship at sea, Prospero, a powerful Duke, asks Ariel, his daughter, to perform a spell to calm the storm. Twelve years ago, Prospero's father was Duke of Milan and a prince of power. Prospero says that by accident, most strange, bountiful Fortune, has brought his enemies to this shore. Ariel foresees the danger Prospero is in and sends him forth to keep them living. Prospero admires Miranda, saying that heaven rains grace on that which breeds between them.

Caliban claims he is subject to a sorcerer that cheated him of the island. Ariel says he lies. Prospero gives Ferdinand his daughter, but if Ferdinand breaks her virgin-knot before ceremonies may be minister'd, no sweet aspersion shall fall. Prospero tells Ariel to incite the rabble to quick motion, for he must bestow upon the eyes of this young couple some vanity of his art. Prospero says he lost his daughter in the last tempest. Ferdinand asks when did he lose her. Prospero says in this last tempest, he lost her. Prospero invites the king and his train to his cell, where they'll take their rest for one night.
John asks Claudio to dissuade his brother from loving Hero, because she is not worthy of his birth.

Pedro tells Claudio that he's wooed Hero on his behalf, and that he's gained her father's approval. Claudio says he's given himself to Beatrice, and Leonato says that they'll get married in seven days.

Aegon, a merchant of Syracusa, is brought before the Duke and his officers for violating the Duke's laws. The Duke explains that since the mortal and intestine jars between Aegon's countrymen and the Duke's have been decreed, both by the Syracusians and themselves, to admit no traffic to their towns. If Aegon is seen at any of the Syracusian marts or fairs, he dies. Aegon and his wife sail to Epidamnum, but before long, they fear death. Aegon's youngest son becomes inquisitive after his brother and asks his father to take him with him in the quest of his brother. Aegon asks the merchant to help him find his brother, who disappeared 5 years ago. Aegon enters the house of Antipholus of Ephesus and finds Adriana and Luciana. Neither his husband nor the slave return'd.

Antipholus of Syracuse hires Drogo, a slave, to find his missing brother. Drogo is beaten for failing to find his brother. Antipholus then hires Drogo to find his missing wife. Drogo is attracted to Adriana, the wife of his master. Adriana is secretly in love with Drogo. Antipholus and Adriana have a secret affair. Adriana calls Drogo by his name, which is against the rules of slavery.

Antipholus of Syracuse hires Drogo to find his missing wife, Adriana. Adriana secretly loves Drogo. Antipholus and Adriana have a secret affair. One day, Drogo beats a man for talking to Adriana. Antipholus orders Drogo to fetch him something to eat. Antipholus and Adriana enter the house and find Drogo. Luciana, Adriana's sister, greets them. Luciana asks Antipholus to use Adriana with more kindness. Antipholus says that he does not know how to think and speak.

Antipholus hires Drogo to find his missing wife, Adriana. Adriana is secretly in love with Drogo. One day, Drogo beats a man for talking to Adriana. Antipholus orders Drogo to fetch him something to eat.
Downstairs, Lord Palmerston receives his guests. Adams would like to stop and ask if William Pitt and the Duke of Wellington laughed so.
Minister Adams remains in England till 1886. Earl Russell suggests intervention might be feasible and calls a Cabinet. Palmerston hesitates but Russell insists.

Adams does not feel Grant as hostile, only uncertain. When in action Grant is superb and safe to follow. Grant frets and irritates Adams, like the Tere. Despite the fatal deception about Grant's political character, Adams enjoys his first winter in Washington. Grant's administration outraged every rule of decency but scores of promising men were ruined.

Dombey sits in the corner of the darkened room with his son, Son, tucked up in a basket bedstead. Dombey has been the sole representative of the Firm for 20 years and has been married to a lady with no heart to give him. There is a girl 6 years before who stole into the chamber unnoticed. Doctor Parker Peps says Nature must be called upon to make a vigorous effort in this instance. If Mrs. Dombey cannot make the effort successfully, a crisis might arise.

Paul grows to be 5 years old and is a pretty little fellow. Paul's abrupt question has immediate reference to the subject of Mr Dombey's thoughts. Paul studies Mrs Pipchin and the cat, night after night as if they were a book of necromancy.

Captain Cuttle lives near the India Docks where there is a bridge that opens to let ships come in. Walter says he just spoke to him. Mrs. MacStinger lets him in. He finds Captain Cuttle in ambush behind the door. There is an earthquake every half-hour. Captain Cuttle bursts out of the door with the suddenness of an explosion. He walks with Walter and pretends to whistle a tune. Mr. Dombey says Paul should be content with their own obligations and not increase them by engaging for other men. Cornelia takes Paul around the house to familiarize him with his new sphere. Walter Gay is sent to fill a junior position in the counting-house at Barbados. Walter feels sorry for being the cause of all this.

Paul never saw him in his room again, whether it were day or night, but he called out, "Don't be sorry for me! Indeed I am quite happy!" This was the beginning of his always saying in the morning that he was a great deal better. One night, Paul thinks of his mother and her picture in the drawing-room downstairs. Walter returns home on the Sunday evening from his long walk. Captain Cuttle goes to Mr. Carker and tells him that Walter is almost a son of his.

Bunsby shakes the Captain's hand and says he's a man of mind and can give an opinion. The Captain introduces Florence to Uncle Sol, who has come home. Florence sees a change in the old man and thinks he's not well.
Captain Cuttle institutes a strict search over the whole house but finds no evidence of Gills' disappearance. He decides to keep house on the premises of Gills himself and run away.

Carker, a gentleman connected to Mr Dombey, is introduced to Mrs Skewton, who is charmed by him. Florence lives with her father, Mr Dombey, in a mansion in Grosvenor Square. She is attracted to him but afraid of him because of his reputation as a courtier.
At dinner, Cousin Feenix rises and says he must call upon the Major to drink a toast. Everyone is delighted. Mr Towlinson returns thanks in a speech replete with feeling.

Harriet, a young woman living in London, is deeply grateful to her brother John for all he has done for her. One day, a gentleman approaches her house and asks for five minutes of her time. He tells her that his brother is an altered man and that he doesn't doubt it.

Captain Cuttle is a man of honor and faith in the Commander of the Cautious Clara. However, as time wears on and Bunsby fails to reappear, the Captain begins to entertain uncomfortable doubts about Bunsby being decoyed to Brig Place as a hostage for his friend. He wonders if Mrs MacStinger had turned back to board.
George, one of the passengers, jumps into the water and lands on somebody, breaking several ribs. The passengers begin to talk loudly about their escape, repeating the same words over and over again.

Marlow reflects on Jim's energy and enthusiasm, and how nothing seems real now. Jim sees him off as he leaves the river. Cornelius follows Marlow from the grave of his late wife to the gate of Jim's compound, hoping he will kindly forget what he said.

Antipholus of Syracuse and his servant Dromio arrive in town. Antipholus plans to view the city and then meet with his mistress Adriana and her sister Luciana for dinner. However, he becomes upset when he realizes that Dromio gave the money he entrusted him with to Adriana. He fears that Dromio has stolen the money.

Angelo and a second merchant discuss how well-respected Antipholus is in the city. Antipholus and Dromio arrive, and Angelo asks Antipholus why he denied having the chain he now wears around his neck. Angelo calls him a villain and the two men draw their swords.

The Abbess says that Adriana's jealous words poisoned Antipholus and made him mad. She says she will not let anyone take him away from the Abbey until she has tried her holy prayers and drugs to make him well again.

Leonato receives news that Don Pedro of Arragon is coming to Messina tonight. Leonato asks how many men have been lost in the battle. Messina says few of any sort and none of name. Don Pedro has bestowed much honor on Claudio, a Florentine. Beatrice warns Benedick that if he catches Claudio, it will cost him a thousand pounds. Pedro arrives with Claudio, Benedick, Balthasar, and John the Bastard. Leonato says they will stay here at least a month. Benedick says he loves Leonato's daughter, Hero. Pedro says Hero is Leonato's only heir.
Bora tells Conrade that he has wooed Margaret, the Lady Hero's gentlewoman, by the name of Hero.

Pedro says Farewell, boy, you know my mind. He will leave you now to your gossiplike humor. His lord, for your many courtesies, he thanks you. He must discontinue your company. His brother the bastard is fled from Messina. For his Lord Lackbeard, he and he will meet.
Ethan hurries to get home to Mattie, hoping that Zeena has not broken anything she values. When he arrives home, he finds Mattie alone in the kitchen.

Mrs. Hale tells Ethan that she was present in the house when Mattie and the other two were brought in. She says that she stayed with Mattie throughout the night and that Mattie woke up just like herself.

Mrs. Hale then says that it's a pity Mattie survived the accident, as she feels that Ethan might have lived if she had died. She adds that the Fromes are now no different from the Fromes in the graveyard.
Fyodor Pavlovitch, Alyosha's father, arrives at the dinner with the Superior and makes a scene, declaring that he will take his son Alexey away from the monastery.
Grigory, the head servant of the Karamazov household, has a strong influence over Fyodor Pavlovitch. He is protective of his second wife, Sofya, who is considered crazy.

Dmitri tells Alyosha that he told Agafya Ivanovna about her father's financial deficit, and that he gave Katerina 5000 roubles to keep the secret. He then tells Alyosha to go to Katerina and tell her that he will never see her again.
Fyodor Pavlovitch tells Alyosha that Ivan intends to murder him. He asks Alyosha to ask Mitya to give up Grushenka once and for all.

Kolya is injured by Ilusha, another boy in his class, in defense of his father. Ilusha has been bedridden for two weeks and is very weak. The doctor tells the captain that he should send his family to Sicily for better climatic conditions.

Enter Count Lodovico, Antonelli, and Gasparo. Lodovico is sentenced to banishment for ruining the noble earldom in three years. Gasparo says the law does not want to steep violent sins in blood and that this gentle penance may end his crimes. Lodovico wonders if great men escape this banishment. There is Paulo Giordano Ursini, the Duke of Brachiano, who seeks to prostitute the honor of Vittoria Corombona. Brachiano says he hopes you don't think nobleman bowl booty. Vittoria enters. Brachiano says he will make her know what is in him. Enter Francisco de Medicis, Cardinal Monticelso, and Isabella.
Brachiano orders Flamineo to carry the body to Cornelia's lodging and that no one tell the duchess about the accident.

Serebrakoff proposes to sell the estate, earning 4-5% on the investment. Until this moment, he has never had a grain of sense in his head thinking that the estate belonged to Sonia.
